# 2. Adday object update problem
There are data updates in the data, no data insert data.

data structure
```
{
    _id: "xxx",
    items: [
        {
            id: 1,
            val: 3
        },
         {
            id: 2,
            val: 3
        },
    ]
}
```
The existence of ID is update, and there is no insertion, the usual full matching of "$addToset can not solve this problem"
I look at ablog the current practice.
```
var update = db.a.update({
    _id: 1,
    "items.id": 9
},{
    "items.$.val": "333"
});

//  sometimes it takes two IO operations
if (update[0] === 0) {
  db.a.update({
    _id: 1,
//Although "$ne" guarantees the atomicity
    "items.id": {
        $ne: 9
    }
  },{
    $push: {
        "items" : { id: 9, val: "123" }
    }
  }
}

```  

Although "$ne" guarantees the atomicity, sometimes it takes two IO operations. Another way is think of id as an attribute name.
```
{
    _id: "xxx",
    items: {
       id_1: {

            val: 3
        }
       id_2: {
            val: 3
        }  
    }
}
```
Want arrays to sore lightweight data, and can also be used as queues and stacks.

# 3.  Mongoose model automatic timestamp setting
I found a lot of open source code in the cnode community without this configuration. Creating the data createTime field will be the current timestamp, and updating the data will also automatically update the updateTime field timestamp. 
```
 new mongoose.Schema({
    name: String,
, {
    timestamps: { createdAt: 'createTime', updatedAt: 'updateTime' }
});

//default name
 new mongoose.Schema({
    name: String,
, {
    timestamps: true
});
```
